#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:78
msgid "Resizing a clip"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:80
msgid ""
"A clip can be resized from its start or end by dragging its left or right"
" edge. If you want a more precise resize, you can place the timeline"
" cursor wherever you want the resize to end and use the menu"
" :menuselection:`Timeline --> Resize Item Start` (default shortcut:"
" :kbd:`1`) or :menuselection:`Timeline --> Resize Item End` (default"
" shortcut: :kbd:`2`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:83
msgid ""
"To even more precisely control the length of a clip, double click it in"
" the timeline and adjust its duration using the **Clip duration** dialog."
" You can have frame-level accuracy with this method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:90
msgid ""
"You can also resize a clip by cutting it with the  `Razor Tool`_ and then"
" deleting the bit you do not want."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:94
msgid "Removing Space Between Clips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/editing.rst:96
msgid ""
"Right click in the space between the clips and choose"
" :menuselection:`Remove Space`. Be aware however that if you have clips"
" on multiple tracks in the timeline and they are not grouped, then"
" removing space may disturb the alignment of the clips between the"
" different tracks – the space is only removed from the timeline where you"
" clicked.  Under this situation it may be safer to use the `Spacer Tool`_."
